THE COMPLETE GUIDE TO CREDIT LAWS
CREDIT REPAIR
ORGANIZATION ACT
(CROA)
Credit Repair Organization Act is a federal law in the United States that regulates
organizations that offer credit repair services to consumers. Its primary purpose is
to protect consumers from deceptive or misleading practices by credit repair
organizations. It aims to ensure transparency and fairness in the credit repair
industry by establishing standards that companies must adhere to when offering
credit repair services.
CROA provides consumers with certain rights, such as the right to receive specific
disclosures before signing a contract, the right to cancel a contract within a
specified period, and protection against false promises or guarantees regarding
credit repair outcomes.
Overall, CROA aims to promote honesty, integrity, and accountability within the
credit repair industry while safeguarding the interests of consumers.
Section 1679: Findings and Purposes
The Congress recognizes that (1) consumers often seek credit repair services to
enhance their credit standing, especially those facing credit challenges. And (2)
Some credit repair companies have engaged in practices that harm consumers,
particularly those with limited financial means and little knowledge of credit
matters.
Therefore, the Credit Repair Organization Act was established to (1) empower
consumers with the information needed to make informed decisions about using
credit repair services. (2) To safeguard the public from unfair or deceptive practices
employed by credit repair organizations.

25
CREDIT REPAIR ORGANIZATION ACT (CROA)
