Section 1679a: Definitions
1. Consumer: An individual.
2. Consumer credit transaction: Any transaction where credit is offered or
extended to an individual for personal, family, or household purposes.
3. Credit repair organization: Any person who uses interstate commerce or the
mail to sell, provide, or perform services for payment, with the purpose of:
• Improving a consumer's credit record, credit history, or credit rating; or
• Providing advice or assistance regarding the activities mentioned above.
It does not include:
• Any nonprofit organization exempts from taxation
• Any creditor assisting a consumer to restructure a debt owed to that creditor;
• Any depository institution or credit union, or their affiliates or subsidiaries
4. Credit: The right a creditor grants to a debtor to defer payment of debt or to
incur debt and defer its payment.
Section 1679b: Prohibited Practices
Under the Credit Repair Organization Act, no person or credit repair company,
along with their salespersons, agents, and representative specialists, is allowed to
do any of the following activities:
1. Receive upfront payment (money or any other valuable consideration)
before the completeness of the services to be performed for or on behalf of
the consumer.
2. Receive payment for the referral of the buyer to a credit grantor who will or
may extend credit for the buyer if the credit is extended to the buyer: (1)
Upon the same terms as those available to the public. (2) Upon the same
terms that would have been extended to the consumer without the assistance
of the credit repair service provider.
3. Make false or misleading promises that are difficult or impossible to fulfill
when offering or selling credit repair services. This includes: (1)

