Section 1679d: Credit Repair Organizations Contracts
A credit repair contract is a legally binding agreement between a consumer and a
credit repair company. It aims to safeguard the interests of both parties and
establish transparent expectations, thereby mitigating potential misunderstandings
or disputes in the future.
Here are some important elements that should be included in the contract:
1. Identification of Parties: This includes the credit repair business name and
address, the representative's or the person performing the service name, and the
consumer's name.
2. Scope of Services: The contract must outline a full and detailed description of
the credit repair services the company will provide to the consumer. This should
include all the guarantees of performance and the estimated date by which the
performance of the services will be complete and the length of period necessary to
perform such services.
3. Fees and Payment Terms: The total cost associated with the services and the
payment terms and conditions, including any upfront payments, recurring fees, or
additional charges.
4. Cancellation and Refund Policy: The contract should clearly state the
consumer's right to cancel within three business days after signing without
incurring any fees. It is required to display "You may cancel this contract
without penalty or obligation at any time before midnight of the 3rd business
day after the date on which you signed the contract. See the attached notice of
cancellation form for an explanation of this right." in boldface type, positioned
close to the area designated for the consumer's signature on the contract.
5. The credit repair service provider must attach a copy of the Notice of
Cancellation when providing the contract. (See a copy of the Notice of
Cancellation in the Consumer’s Right to Cancel Section).

