6. Separate document of “Consumer Credit File Rights Under State and
Federal Law," from the written contract or other agreement.
7. Guarantees and Disclaimers: If the company offers any guarantees or
assurances regarding credit repair outcomes, they must be disclosed clearly, along
with any disclaimers or limitations.
8. Confidentiality: The contract includes provisions to protect the confidentiality
of the consumer's personal and financial information.
9. Signature of Parties: To seal the contract, signatures from the consumer and a
credit repair company representative must be included. This indicates their
agreement to the terms outlined in the contract.
A copy of the complete contract, a disclosure statement, a notice of cancellation,
and other documents that the credit repair company requires the consumer to sign
should be given to the consumer at the time the contract and the documents are
signed.
Section 1679e: Right to Cancel Contract
Consumers can cancel any contract with a credit repair organization without
penalty or obligation. They can do so by notifying the organization of their
intention to cancel before midnight of the third business day following the date the
contract becomes enforceable.
In relation to this, The CROA requires each contract to include a "Notice of
Cancellation" form in boldface type, allowing consumers to easily understand their
cancellation rights. This form provides instructions for cancellation, including
where and how to send the cancellation notice.

