FAIR CREDIT
REPORTING ACT
(FCRA)
The Fair Credit Reporting Act is a federal law regulating the collection,
dissemination, and use of consumer credit information.
The FCRA provides consumers with rights regarding their credit reports, including
the right to access their reports, dispute inaccuracies, and limit who can access
their credit information. It also imposes obligations on credit reporting agencies,
creditors, and other entities that handle consumer credit information to respect the
consumer's privacy rights and ensure the information is accurate and properly used.
Section 601: Short title
This title may be cited as the “Fair Credit Reporting Act.”
Section 602: Congressional Findings and Statement of
Purpose
(a) Accuracy and Fairness of Credit Reporting
Congress finds that:
1. The banking system relies on fair and accurate credit reporting. Inaccurate
reports harm the banking system's efficiency, and unfair methods reduce public
confidence, which is essential for the system's operation.
2. There is a complex system for investigating and evaluating consumers'
creditworthiness, credit standing, capacity, character, and reputation.

36
FAIR CREDIT REPORTING ACT (FCRA)
THE COMPLETE GUIDE TO CREDIT LAWS
3. Consumer reporting agencies play a crucial role in collecting and assessing
consumer credit and other information.
4. It is important to ensure these agencies handle their significant responsibilities
with fairness, impartiality, and respect for consumers' privacy rights.
(b) Reasonable Procedures
The purpose of the FCRA is to ensure that consumer reporting agencies adopt
reasonable procedures to meet commerce needs for consumer credit, personnel,
insurance, and other information. These procedures must be fair, equitable, and
respect confidentiality, accuracy, relevance, and proper use of such information
as required by the FCRA.
Section 603: Definitions; Rules of Construction
(a) Definitions and rules of construction set forth in this section are applicable for
the purposes of this title.
(b) The term "person" means any individual, partnership, corporation, trust, estate,
cooperative, association, government or governmental subdivision or agency, or
other entity.
(c) The term "consumer" means an individual.
(d) The term “consumer report”
(1) In general
It means any written, oral, or other communication of any information by a
consumer reporting agency bearing on a consumer's creditworthiness, credit
standing, credit capacity, character, general reputation, personal characteristics, or
mode of living which is used or expected to be used or collected in whole or in part
for the purpose of serving as a factor in establishing the consumer's eligibility for
the following:
• Credit or insurance to be used primarily for personal, family, or household
purposes.
• Employment purposes.

