Section 605: Requirements Relating to Information
Contained in Consumer Reports
(a) Information Excluded from Consumer Reports
Except as authorized under exempted cases, a consumer reporting agency cannot
include the following information in a consumer report:
1. Bankruptcy cases older than 10 years from the date of relief or adjudication.
2. Civil suits, judgments, and arrest records older than 7 years or beyond the statute
of limitations, whichever is longer.
3. Paid tax liens older than 7 years from the payment date.
4. Accounts placed for collection or written off older than 7 years.
5. Any other negative information (except criminal convictions) older than 7 years.
6. The name, address, and phone number of any medical information provider,
unless:
• This information is restricted or coded so it doesn't identify the provider or
services.
• The report is for an insurance company related to non-property and
casualty insurance.
7. Information about a veteran's medical debt if the debt is less than a year old and
the agency knows it is related to a veteran.
8. Information about a veteran's medical debt that has been fully paid or settled, if
it was previously reported as delinquent, charged off, or in collection, and the
agency knows it is related to a veteran.
(b) Exempted Cases
The rules in paragraphs 1 through 5 of the previous subsections do not apply to
consumer credit reports used for:

