(C) Notice to third parties: A consumer reporting agency may advise a third party
that a security freeze has been placed with respect to a consumer.
(3) Removal of a security freeze
(A) General Rule: A consumer reporting agency shall remove a security freeze
placed on the consumer report of a consumer only in the following cases:
• Upon the direct request of the consumer.
• The security freeze was placed due to a material misrepresentation of fact by
the consumer.
(B) Notice if removal not by request: If a consumer reporting agency removes
a security freeze due to a material misrepresentation of fact by the consumer,
the agency shall notify the consumer in writing before removing the security
freeze.
(C) Removal of security freeze by consumer request: Except when the
security freeze was placed due to a material misrepresentation of fact by the
consumer, a security freeze will remain in place until the consumer directly
requests its removal. Once a consumer reporting agency receives the request
and upon proper identification from the consumer, the agency, free of charge,
remove the security freeze not later than:
• For requests made by toll-free telephone or secure electronic means, the
freeze will be removed within 1 hour.
• For requests made by mail, the freeze will be removed within 3 business
days.
(D) Third-party requests: If a third-party requests access to a consumer report
that has a security freeze, and the consumer does not allow such consumer
report to be accessed, the third-party can consider the application incomplete.
(E) Temporary removal of security freeze: If a consumer directly requests a
temporary removal of a security freeze, the consumer reporting agency must lift
the freeze for the specified period by the consumer.

