Section 605B: Block Of Information Resulting from
Identity Theft
The FCRA addresses identity theft by outlining the following guides for consumer
reporting agencies to handle fraud alerts.
(a) Block
A consumer reporting agency must block any information in a consumer's file that
the consumer identifies as stemming from alleged identity theft. This action must
occur within 4 business days of the agency receiving the following:
• Appropriate proof of the consumer's identity
• A copy of an identity theft report
• Identification of the relevant information by the consumer, and
• A statement from the consumer affirming that the information is unrelated to
any transaction they conducted.
(b) Notification
A consumer reporting agency shall promptly notify the furnisher of information
identified by the consumer:

71
FAIR CREDIT REPORTING ACT (FCRA)
THE COMPLETE GUIDE TO CREDIT LAWS
• That the information may be a result of identity theft;
• That an identity theft report has been filed;
• That a block has been requested under this section; and
• Of the effective dates of the block.
(c) Authority to Decline or Rescind
(1) General Rule
The credit agency can choose not to block or may rescind a block from a
consumer's information if it reasonably believes that:
• The block was requested by mistake, or the information was blocked
incorrectly.
• The consumer provided false information relevant to the request.
• The consumer obtained possession of goods, services, or money as a result
of the blocked transaction or transactions.
(2) Notification to consumer
If a block of information is declined or removed under this subsection, the affected
consumer shall be promptly notified in the same way as they are notified of the
reinsertion of information under section 611(a)(5)(B) - Procedure in Case of
Disputed Accuracy (Requirements Relating to Reinsertion of Previously Deleted
Material).
(3) Significance of Block
If a consumer reporting agency removes a block, the information in the consumer's
file before the block does not prove whether the consumer knew or should have
known about receiving any goods, services, or money as a result of the block.
