Section 626: Disclosures to FBI for
Counterintelligence Purposes
(a) Identity of Financial Institutions
Identity of financial institutions: A consumer reporting agency must provide the
FBI with the names and addresses of all financial institutions where a consumer
has or had an account, if the agency has that information. This must be done when
the FBI presents a written request, signed by a high-ranking official, certifying that
the information is needed for an authorized investigation related to international
terrorism or clandestine intelligence activities. The investigation must not be based
solely on activities protected by the First Amendment.
(b) Identifying Information
Despite the rules in section 604 [Permissible Purposes of Consumer Reports] or
any other part of this subchapter, a consumer reporting agency must provide the
FBI with a consumer's name, address, former addresses, and places of employment
upon receiving a written request. This request must:
• Include a specific term identifying the consumer or account in question.
• Be signed by the FBI Director or a designee not lower than a Deputy
Assistant Director at Bureau headquarters or a Special Agent in Charge of a
Bureau field office.
• Certify compliance with this subsection.
The certification can only be made if the Director or designee has determined in
writing that the information is needed for an authorized investigation related to

