accumulated finance charge and the balance is applied to the unpaid amount
financed; or
(B) the rate determined by any method prescribed by the Bureau as a method
which materially simplifies computation while retaining reasonable accuracy
as compared with the rate determined under subparagraph (A).
(2) in the case of any extension of credit under an open end credit plan, as the
quotient (expressed as a percentage) of the total finance charge for the period to
which it relates divided by the amount upon which the finance charge for that
period is based, multiplied by the number of such periods in a year.
(b) Computation of Rate of Finance Charges for Balances Within a
Specified Range
If a creditor charges the same finance rate for balances within a certain range, the
annual percentage rate should be calculated based on the middle balance of that
range. However, if the Bureau finds this method to be misleading or not
meaningful, they can require a different calculation method through regulation.
(c) Allowable Tolerances for Purposes of Compliance with
Disclosure Requirements
An annual percentage rate (APR) disclosure is considered accurate if it is within
0.125% (1/8 of 1 per centum), more or less than the actual rate, or rounded to the
nearest 0.25% (1/4 of 1 per centum). The Bureau may permit a larger tolerance for
easier compliance when irregular payments are involved.
(d) Use of Rate Tables or Charts Having Allowable Variance from
Determined Rates
The Bureau may allow the use of rate tables or charts that show annual percentage
rates (APRs) varying within certain tolerances from the calculated rate. These

