Section 1610: Effect on Other Laws
(a) Inconsistent Provisions; Procedures Applicable for
Determination
1) Except as noted in subsection (Certain credit and charge card application and
solicitation disclosure provisions), this part and parts B and C do not change or
cancel state laws about sharing information in credit transactions. They only
change state laws if there's a conflict, and then only to the extent of that conflict.
Upon its own motion or upon the request of any creditor, state, or other interested
party, the Bureau will check if there's a conflict. If a state-required disclosure
conflicts, creditors in that state can't use it and won't get in trouble under state law
for not using it, even if the Bureau later changes its mind or a court says it's wrong
for any reason.
2) Upon its own motion or upon the request of any creditor, state, or other
interested party, the Bureau will check if a state-required disclosure means the
same thing as a disclosure required by this subchapter. If it does, creditors in that
state can use the state-required disclosure instead of the one required by this
subchapter, but they still have to disclose the annual percentage rate and finance
charge as required. This doesn't apply to disclosures needed for certain mortgages
under specific sections.

