also clearly present the following information as required by the Bureau.

358
TRUTH IN LENDING ACT (TILA) - A.K.A. CONSUMER CREDIT COST DISCLOSURE
THE COMPLETE GUIDE TO CREDIT LAWS
(1) Loan fees and opening cost estimates
Any loan fee calculated as a percentage of the account's credit limit and an
estimated total of other account-opening fees, stated as a single amount or
reasonable range based on the creditor's experience.
(2) Periodic rates
In any case in which periodic rates may be used to compute the finance charge, the
periodic rates expressed as an annual percentage rate.
(3) Highest annual percentage rate
The highest annual percentage rate which may be imposed under the plan.
(4) Other information
Any other information the Bureau may by regulation require.
(b) Tax Deductibility
(1) General Rule
If any advertisement described in the general rule contains a statement that any
interest expense incurred with respect to the plan is or may be tax deductible, the
advertisement shall not be misleading with respect to such deductibility.
(2) Credit in Excess of Fair Market Value
Each paper or online advertisement for credit exceeding the dwelling's fair market
value must include a clear and conspicuous statement that:
(A) the interest on the portion of the credit extension that is greater than the
fair market value of the dwelling is not tax deductible for Federal income tax
purposes; and
(B) the consumer should consult a tax adviser for further information
regarding the deductibility of interest and charges.
(c) Certain Terms Prohibited
No advertisement with respect to any home equity account may refer to such loan
as "free money" or use other terms determined by the Bureau by regulation to be
misleading.

