Section 1665d: Reasonable Penalty Fees on Open-End
Consumer Credit Plans
(a) General Rule
Any penalty fee or charge that a card issuer imposes on a credit card account under
an open-end consumer credit plan, such as late payment fees or over-the-limit fees,
must be reasonable and proportionate to the specific issue or violation of the
cardholder agreement.
(b) Rulemaking required
The Bureau, in consultation with the Comptroller of the Currency, the Board of
Directors of the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation, the Director of the Office
of Thrift Supervision, and the National Credit Union Administration Board, shall
issue final rules not later than 9 months after May 22, 2009, to establish standards
for assessing whether the amount of any penalty fee or charge described under
subsection (a) is reasonable and proportional to the omission or violation to which
the fee or charge relates. Subsection (a) shall become effective 15 months after
May 22, 2009.
(c) Considerations
In issuing rules required by this section, the Bureau shall consider:
(1) the cost incurred by the creditor from such omission or violation;
(2) the deterrence of such omission or violation by the cardholder;
(3) the conduct of the cardholder; and
(4) such other factors as the Bureau may deem necessary or appropriate.
(d) Differentiation Permitted

