The required disclosures under this section can be included directly in the lease
contract that the lessee signs. The Bureau may also permit, through regulation, that
any part of the required information may be presented as estimates if the lessor
does not have exact information at the time of disclosure.
Section 1667b: Lessee's Liability on Expiration or
Termination of Lease
(a) Estimated Residual Value of Property as Basis; Presumptions;
Action by Lessor for Excess Liability; Mutually Agreeable Final
Adjustment

379
TRUTH IN LENDING ACT (TILA) - A.K.A. CONSUMER CREDIT COST DISCLOSURE
THE COMPLETE GUIDE TO CREDIT LAWS
If a lessee's liability at the end of a consumer lease is based on the estimated
residual value of the leased property, this estimate must reasonably reflect the
expected actual fair market value of the property when the lease ends. There is a
rebuttable presumption that the estimated residual value is unreasonable if it
exceeds the actual residual value by more than three times the average monthly
payment specified in the lease.
Furthermore, if the lessee has liability at the end of the lease, there is a rebuttable
presumption that the lessor's estimated residual value is not made in good faith if it
exceeds the actual residual value by more than three times the average monthly
payment. In such cases, the lessor cannot collect the excess amount from the lessee
unless they win a legal action regarding this excess liability. The lessor is also
responsible for paying the lessee's reasonable attorney fees in these actions.
These presumptions do not apply if the excess estimated residual value is due to
physical damage beyond normal wear and tear or excessive use. The lease can
outline standards for acceptable wear and use, as long as these standards are
reasonable. Lastly, this subsection does not prevent a willing lessee from reaching
a mutual agreement with the lessor for a final adjustment regarding any excess
residual liability, provided that this agreement is made after the lease has ended.
(b) Penalties and Charges for Delinquency, Default, Or Early
Termination
Penalties or other charges for delinquency, default, or early termination may be
specified in the lease but only at an amount which is reasonable in the light of the
anticipated or actual harm caused by the delinquency, default, or early termination,
the difficulties of proof of loss, and the inconvenience or nonfeasibility of
otherwise obtaining an adequate remedy.

