(ii) the name and dates of any publication referred to in clause (i)(II);
and
(D) includes any other information which the Bureau determines necessary
to carry out this part.
(2) Establishment of Toll-Free Number
(A) General Rule
In the case of a radio broadcast advertisement that includes a referral to a
toll-free telephone number, the lessor who offers the consumer lease shall:
(i) establish such a toll-free telephone number not later than the date
on which the advertisement including the referral is broadcast;
(ii) maintain such telephone number for a period of not less than 10
days, beginning on the date of any such broadcast; and
(iii) provide the information required under subsection (a) with
respect to the lease to any person who calls such number.
(B) Form of information
The information required to be provided under subparagraph (A)(iii) shall be
provided verbally or, if requested by the consumer, in written form.
(3) No effect on other law
Nothing in this subsection shall affect the requirements of Federal law as such
requirements apply to advertisement by any medium other than radio broadcast.
Section 1667d. Civil Liability of Lessors

383
TRUTH IN LENDING ACT (TILA) - A.K.A. CONSUMER CREDIT COST DISCLOSURE
THE COMPLETE GUIDE TO CREDIT LAWS
(a) Grounds for Maintenance of Action
Any lessor who fails to comply with any requirement imposed under section 1667a
[Consumer Lease Disclosures] or 1667b [Lessee's Liability on Expiration or
Termination of Lease] of this title with respect to any person is liable to such
person as provided in section 1640 [Civil Liability] of this title.
(b) Additional Grounds for Maintenance of Action; "Creditor"
Defined
Any lessor who fails to comply with any requirement imposed under section 1667c
[Consumer Lease Advertising; Liability of Advertising Media] of this title with
respect to any person who suffers actual damage from the violation is liable to such
person as provided in the Civil Liability section. For the purposes of this section,
the term "creditor" as used in sections 1640 [Civil Liability] and 1641[Liability of
Assignees] of this title shall include a lessor as defined in this part.
(c) Jurisdiction of Courts; Time Limitation
Regardless of section 1640(e) [Civil Liability - Jurisdiction of courts] of this title,
any legal action under this section can be taken in any U.S. district court or other
court that has the authority to hear the case. Actions claiming a failure to disclose
information or comply with the requirements must be filed within one year after
the lease agreement ends.
Section 1667e: Applicability Of State Laws;
Exemptions by Bureau from Leasing Requirements

384
TRUTH IN LENDING ACT (TILA) - A.K.A. CONSUMER CREDIT COST DISCLOSURE
THE COMPLETE GUIDE TO CREDIT LAWS
(a) This section does not cancel, change, or exempt anyone from following state
laws related to consumer leases, unless those laws conflict with this part. In such
cases, only the conflicting parts will be affected. The Bureau has the authority to
decide if any inconsistencies exist. However, the Bureau cannot say that a state law
is inconsistent with this part if that law offers more protection and benefits to
consumers.
(b) The Bureau shall create regulations to exempt any category of lease
transactions in a state from the requirements of this part if it finds that the state’s
laws for those transactions are very similar to the requirements here or provide
greater protection and benefits for consumers, and if there are sufficient
enforcement measures in place.
Section 1667f: Regulations
(a) Regulations Authorized
(1) General Rule
The Bureau shall prescribe regulations to update and clarify the requirements and
definitions applicable to lease disclosures and contracts, and any other issues
specifically related to consumer leasing, to the extent that the Bureau determines
such action to be necessary:
(A) to carry out this part;
(B) to prevent any circumvention of this part; or
(C) to facilitate compliance with the requirements of the part.
(2) Classifications, Adjustments
Any regulations prescribed under the general rule may contain classifications and
differentiations, and may provide for adjustments and exceptions for any class of
transactions, as the Bureau considers appropriate.

